Briefer

Everyone asks "What is the standard deviation?", yet nobody ever asks "Why is the standard deviation?". Today we're going to answer the second question, since no teacher ever gave me a satisfying answer.

The standard deviation is one of the most widespread metrics in the field of statistics, and anyone that has any interest in statistics will know the standard deviation formula by heart:

But most people don't know why the standard deviation is defined like this. If you ask a statistics professor, they'll mumble something about "average distance to the mean" or variance of independent variables being additive. Today we're going to get to the bottom of the why we use this particular formula.

But first, why do we need the standard deviation? And what exactly does it tells us? In short, it's used to describe how "spread out" a dataset is, in other words, how far away the data points are from the mean. This is very useful information since we can talk about a specific characteristic: variability, using only one number that is easy to calculate. Below are two datasets for the ages of teachers in a school:

Even though they have the same mean, it's clear that these populations are not at all alike. This difference is invisible when we're talking about their mean, and that's where the standard deviation comes in. It is a measure of variability, in other words, how much each data point deviates from the mean. This is one of the most basic characteristics of a dataset, and it helps us ask the right questions and come to the right conclusions.

Now that we know that we want to calculate variability in a dataset, how would we go about doing it? Well, a first hunch would be to simply take the average of the individual distances to the mean! I mean, why not? Taking the average distance to the mean would tell us how far away from the mean a point is on average.

Alright, let's do this! Our new measure will be called the ADM (Average Distance to Mean):

Calculating this for the two datasets give us: and . Hold on, what's this? Well, of course, the average distance to the mean will always be 0. Since that's literally the definition of mean: the positive and negative differences cancel each other out and we always get 0.

Looking at the graph above we can see that the green and red areas add up to the same amount. This is unavoidable when dealing with the mean, so we must think of another way. Since we only want the distance, couldn't we sum the absolute differences and get their average? Congratulations! You have just discovered the formula for the Mean Absolute Deviation (MAD):

This is a measure which is simple to calculate and tells us how much variability our data has. But why is it different from the standard deviation? Isn't that what we wanted?

In a sense, yes. But MAD has some disadvantages which are not immediately clear. For starters, MAD treats all deviations equally, while for variability what we actually want is to give larger weight to outliers. Let's say we're looking at the exam scores of two different classrooms, which one of these would you say is more varied? I.e. which one has the largest average deviation from the mean?


I'd wager most people would say that classroom A is more varied than classroom B, due to the 10 students that graded between 7 and 8. But what we see when calculating the MAD is a different thing, that classroom B's MAD is higher than classroom A's. This is not intuitive, and is why we generally want outliers to be given greater weight.

But the other, more important point is that the MAD function is not differentiable. This is due to the absolute function's discontinuity at 0. This may not seem like a big deal at first, but differentiating a function is useful in a lot of situations, specially for symbolic manipulation, and statisticians love symbolic manipulation since that means they don't actually have to compute anything right up to the end.

We had a good idea in taking the absolute difference of each point, but that is also what makes MAD more troublesome to work with. So we must find another way. What's another well-known operation whose output is always positive? The square! What if we sum the square of each difference to the mean? That way we get no negatives, and as a bonus make outliers more significant.

Well done! You have just discovered the variance, but this still is not what we want, since we have the average squared distance to the mean. We solve this by taking the square root, thus, we have finally arrived at the standard deviation's formula:

It's difficult to understate how widespread the use of the standard deviation is: It's used to define the Gaussian distribution, measure the volatility of an asset's return, the consistency of products, the effectiveness of medical treatments, among countless other things. This is in spite of the fact that it's relatively recent, being named in 1894, and just goes to show how useful it really is.

Its universality is also what made me struggle with its origins, because it seemed like such an arbitrary decision. But that's exactly what it was! The field of statistics (and mathematics as well) is researched by humans, who have preferences and opinions that don't necessarily stand up to mathematical rigor, and that's ok. Statisticians settled on the standard deviation because they liked it better than MAD - they of course had their reasons which we just discussed - but at the end of the day it was an arbitrary decision. And making that clear is important.
